UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['The coordinate (shoelace) method gives the area of any closed traverse directly from the corner coordinates: A = ½|Σ(x_i(y_{i+1} − y_{i−1}))|.','The DMD method is the hand-computation equivalent that uses latitudes and double meridian distances; it yields the identical area.','Always work around the polygon in a consistent direction and divide the final double area by two; convert square feet to acres by dividing by 43,560.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Compute the area of a closed polygon from station coordinates using the coordinate (shoelace) method.','Compute the same area by the traditional Double Meridian Distance (DMD) method and explain why it gives the identical result.','Convert a computed area in square feet to acres and report area with appropriate significant figures.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='429a1bdd-bc34-4723-bb7d-daf1db4d2665';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='429a1bdd-bc34-4723-bb7d-daf1db4d2665';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Triangle area from two sides and the included angle is A = ½·a·b·sin C; from three sides it is Heron''s formula.','Any polygon can be triangulated and its total area found by summing triangle areas.','Irregular curved boundaries are handled with offsets: the trapezoidal rule averages adjacent offsets; Simpson''s one-third rule fits parabolas and is more accurate for an even number of equal intervals.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Compute the area of a triangle from two sides and the included angle, and from three known sides (Heron''s formula).','Decompose an irregular polygon into triangles and sum their areas.','Compute the area between a traverse line and an irregular (curved) boundary using offsets, the trapezoidal rule, and Simpson''s one-third rule.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='a9daa1c2-b0ae-40ab-ac31-c0295afe69b0';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='a9daa1c2-b0ae-40ab-ac31-c0295afe69b0';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=35, key_takeaways=ARRAY['Land division (partition) requires solving geometry so that a cut line encloses an exact target area.','Common cases are a dividing line parallel to a side, a line through a fixed point, and a strip cut off a parcel.','In Texas, subdividing land triggers platting, plat-approval, and (in many counties) statutory requirements; the surveyor must also avoid creating landlocked tracts.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Lay out a line that divides a parcel into two parts of specified area (e.g., for inheritance or sale).','Solve the common cases: a line parallel to a given side, a line through a fixed point, and cutting off a required acreage.','State the surveyor''s professional and Texas legal constraints when subdividing land.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='704310c8-fb7a-49e1-8912-62f081890afa';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='704310c8-fb7a-49e1-8912-62f081890afa';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=40, key_takeaways=ARRAY['The average-end-area method gives volume V = L·(A1 + A2)/2 between two cross-sections separated by length L.','The prismoidal formula V = L·(A1 + 4·Am + A2)/6 is exact for prismoid solids and is more accurate when end areas change non-linearly.','Earthwork volumes are reported in cubic yards (÷27 from cubic feet); cut and fill are tracked separately because soil shrinks/swells.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Compute end areas of cut and fill cross-sections and apply the average-end-area formula between stations.','Apply the prismoidal formula and the prismoidal correction, and know when each is required.','Convert volumes between cubic feet and cubic yards and distinguish cut from fill (earthwork basics).']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='de47d43a-6820-4784-96d0-40a3cfaa4621';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='de47d43a-6820-4784-96d0-40a3cfaa4621';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=30, key_takeaways=ARRAY['In the contour-area method, each contour encloses a horizontal area; volume is integrated between contours using the contour interval as the ''length.''','Between two contours: V = (contour interval)·(A_lower + A_upper)/2 (average-end-area), or use the prismoidal formula across three contours.','Contour methods are ideal for reservoirs, ponds, borrow pits, and stockpiles where contours are easier to map than cross-sections.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Compute the volume of earth or water between successive contour lines using the average-end-area and prismoidal approaches.','Compute reservoir/stockpile volumes by planimetering contour areas and integrating between contour intervals.','Recognize when the contour-area method is preferred over cross-sections (large irregular sites, ponds, stockpiles).']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='133e303e-b95a-45de-8d33-b39ce8eb2d40';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='133e303e-b95a-45de-8d33-b39ce8eb2d40';
UPDATE learning_lessons SET content_migrated=true, estimated_minutes=40, key_takeaways=ARRAY['An earthwork tabulation computes volume between each pair of stations (average-end-area or prismoidal), then sums cut and fill separately.','Apply shrinkage to fill and swell to excavated/hauled material before balancing; a balance point is where cumulative cut equals cumulative fill.','Always convert to cubic yards (÷27), label cut vs. fill, and report only as many figures as the field data support.']::text[], learning_objectives=ARRAY['Carry out a complete station-by-station earthwork tabulation from end areas to total cut and fill volumes.','Apply shrinkage and swell factors and locate the balance point where cut equals fill.','Quality-check earthwork computations and present results with correct units and significant figures.']::text[], status='published', is_published=true, review_status='approved', updated_at=now() WHERE id='df466917-ac9e-4799-a168-8475631ca487';
DELETE FROM lesson_blocks WHERE lesson_id='df466917-ac9e-4799-a168-8475631ca487';
  'eeee0950-0000-0000-0000-000000000001', 'Parcel area by coordinates (shoelace)', 'Parcel area by coordinates (shoelace)', 'Area and Volume — Area by Coordinates', 'Shoelace method', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'A closed four-sided parcel has corner coordinates (X, Y), in feet, of A(0, 0), B({{xb}}, 0), C({{xb}}, {{yc}}), and D(0, {{yd}}), taken counter-clockwise. Using the coordinate (shoelace) method, what is the parcel area in ACRES? (1 acre = 43,560 sq ft.)', '(0.5*abs(xb*(yc-0) + xb*(yd-0)))/43560', '{"decimals":3,"unit":"ac","tolerance":0.005}', '[{"name":"xb","type":"integer","min":300,"max":700},{"name":"yc","type":"integer","min":250,"max":600},{"name":"yd","type":"integer","min":250,"max":600}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"areaSqFt","formula":"0.5*abs(xb*(yc-0) + xb*(yd-0))"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Apply the shoelace sum","formula":"2A = Σ(x_i·y_{i+1} − x_{i+1}·y_i)","calculation_template":"Cross-multiply A(0,0), B({{xb}},0), C({{xb}},{{yc}}), D(0,{{yd}}) around the loop"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Double area in square feet","result_template":"2A = {{xb}}·{{yc}} + {{xb}}·{{yd}} ; A = {{areaSqFt:f1}} sq ft"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Convert to acres","result_template":"{{areaSqFt:f1}} ÷ 43,560 = {{_answer}} ac"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'The shoelace method yields a double area of {{xb}}·{{yc}} + {{xb}}·{{yd}}; halving gives {{areaSqFt:f1}} sq ft, which is {{areaSqFt:f1}} ÷ 43,560 = {{_answer}} acres.', 'c1000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', ARRAY['buildout','module-9','practice']::text[], true, 'buildout:m9');
  'eeee0950-0000-0000-0000-000000000002', 'Strip area by average of two end offsets', 'Strip area by average of two end offsets', 'Area and Volume — Area by Offsets', 'Average end offsets', 'numeric_input', 'easy', 'A strip of land between a straight base line and an irregular boundary is {{length}} ft long. The perpendicular offset to the boundary is {{o1}} ft at one end and {{o2}} ft at the other end. Approximating the strip as a trapezoid, what is its area in square feet (average of the two end offsets × length)?', 'length*(o1+o2)/2', '{"decimals":1,"unit":"sq ft","tolerance":0.5}', '[{"name":"length","type":"integer","min":200,"max":1000},{"name":"o1","type":"integer","min":10,"max":50},{"name":"o2","type":"integer","min":10,"max":50}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"avgOffset","formula":"(o1+o2)/2"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Average the end offsets","calculation_template":"({{o1}} + {{o2}}) ÷ 2 = {{avgOffset:f1}} ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Multiply by length","result_template":"{{avgOffset:f1}} × {{length}} = {{_answer}} sq ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Treating the strip as a trapezoid, area = average offset × length = (({{o1}}+{{o2}})/2) × {{length}} = {{_answer}} sq ft.', 'c1000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', ARRAY['buildout','module-9','practice']::text[], true, 'buildout:m9');
  'eeee0950-0000-0000-0000-000000000003', 'Volume by average end area to cubic yards', 'Volume by average end area to cubic yards', 'Area and Volume — Earthwork Volume', 'Average-end-area', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'Two cross-sections {{length}} ft apart have cut end areas of {{a1}} sq ft and {{a2}} sq ft. Using the average-end-area method, V = L·(A1+A2)/2, what is the cut volume between the sections in CUBIC YARDS? (1 cu yd = 27 cu ft.)', '(length*(a1+a2)/2)/27', '{"decimals":1,"unit":"cy","tolerance":0.5}', '[{"name":"length","type":"integer","min":50,"max":150},{"name":"a1","type":"integer","min":60,"max":200},{"name":"a2","type":"integer","min":60,"max":200}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"volCuFt","formula":"length*(a1+a2)/2"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Average the end areas","calculation_template":"({{a1}} + {{a2}}) ÷ 2 sq ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Volume in cubic feet","formula":"L × average area","calculation_template":"{{length}} × (({{a1}}+{{a2}})/2) = {{volCuFt:f1}} cu ft"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Convert to cubic yards","result_template":"{{volCuFt:f1}} ÷ 27 = {{_answer}} cy"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Average-end-area volume = {{length}} × (({{a1}}+{{a2}})/2) = {{volCuFt:f1}} cubic feet; dividing by 27 gives {{_answer}} cubic yards.', 'c1000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', ARRAY['buildout','module-9','practice']::text[], true, 'buildout:m9');
  'eeee0950-0000-0000-0000-000000000004', 'Trapezoidal-rule area from equally spaced offsets', 'Trapezoidal-rule area from equally spaced offsets', 'Area and Volume — Area by Offsets', 'Trapezoidal rule', 'numeric_input', 'medium', 'Perpendicular offsets to an irregular boundary are taken at a common interval of {{d}} ft. Five offsets are recorded: end offsets {{h0}} ft and {{h4}} ft, and interior offsets {{h1}} ft, {{h2}} ft, and {{h3}} ft. Using the trapezoidal rule, A = d·[(h0+hn)/2 + (interior offsets)], what is the area in square feet?', 'd*((h0+h4)/2 + (h1+h2+h3))', '{"decimals":1,"unit":"sq ft","tolerance":0.5}', '[{"name":"d","type":"integer","min":20,"max":60},{"name":"h0","type":"integer","min":8,"max":40},{"name":"h1","type":"integer","min":8,"max":40},{"name":"h2","type":"integer","min":8,"max":40},{"name":"h3","type":"integer","min":8,"max":40},{"name":"h4","type":"integer","min":8,"max":40}]'::jsonb, '[{"name":"ends","formula":"(h0+h4)/2"},{"name":"interior","formula":"h1+h2+h3"}]'::jsonb, '[{"step_number":1,"title":"Average the two end offsets","calculation_template":"({{h0}} + {{h4}}) ÷ 2 = {{ends:f1}} ft"},{"step_number":2,"title":"Sum the interior offsets","calculation_template":"{{h1}} + {{h2}} + {{h3}} = {{interior:f1}} ft"},{"step_number":3,"title":"Multiply by the interval","result_template":"{{d}} × ({{ends:f1}} + {{interior:f1}}) = {{_answer}} sq ft"}]'::jsonb, '{"method":"none"}'::jsonb, 'Trapezoidal rule: A = d·[(h0+hn)/2 + Σ interior] = {{d}} × (({{h0}}+{{h4}})/2 + {{h1}}+{{h2}}+{{h3}}) = {{_answer}} sq ft.', 'c1000009-0000-0000-0000-000000000009', ARRAY['buildout','module-9','practice']::text[], true, 'buildout:m9');
COMMIT;
